http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: District of Columbia Health Education Standards

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The health and health-related behaviors of students have a direct bearing on their ability to do well in school and to navigate successfully through the larger community. Health education in schools can effectively enable students to develop the knowledge and skills they need to reduce health risks, while simultaneously enhancing their academic achievement. Positive health behaviors initiated early in life should decrease the possibility of disease, disability, and premature death later in life. Far too many young people die in the District of Columbia because of unintentional injuries or as the result of violent behavior. Too many others compromise their well-being through unhealthy behaviors, such as using alcohol, tobacco, or other drugs. Comprehensive health education will equip our students with the knowledge and skills they need to advance personal, family, school, and community health.
Students comprehend concepts related to health promotion and disease prevention.
Emotional Health
Recognize, describe, express, and manage various feelings, such as happiness, surprise, anger, fear, and sadness.
Explain and demonstrate how to handle disappointments, frustrations, and successes appropriately.
Express awareness of oneself and confidence in one's own characteristics, preferences, and expanding abilities.
Explain that all human beings have the need for love.
Explain differences between various emotions; and describe constructive methods to accommodate a variety of feelings, including the feelings of others.
Express feelings in healthy ways in order to create positive relationships.
Explain how feeling good about oneself and being able to identify what makes one unique and special are signs of emotional health.
Explain and demonstrate ways to cope with rejection, loss, and separation.
Know how to cope with bullies and tell adults about problems.
Explain how exercising and getting enough sleep help people feel better emotionally.
Illustrate how too much stress can reduce the body's resistance to disease.
Know that the healing power of words enhance relationships at every level.
Describe the relationship between physical health and emotional health.
Describe the causes and symptoms of, and myths about, common mental and emotional illnesses.
Understand that unkind words and gossip are a form of verbal violence, and work to stop unkind words and bullying.
Discuss how mental, emotional, social, and physical health are interrelated; and describe how problems in one dimension can influence another.
Compare and contrast positive and negative responses to criticism and disappointment.
Monitor one's behavior around others, check one's speech and body language, and alter any bad or offensive habits.
Explain how appropriate mental health care can help prevent, detect, and treat serious mental health problems, such as anxiety disorders, mood disorders, and suicide.
Assess the effects of peer pressure and offer -effective ways to cope with negative influences and -bullying.
Identify warning signs of depression.
Recommend ways to help a friend or family member deal with emotional conflicts or problems.
School & Community Health
Respect and care for the classroom environment and materials.
Identify basic safety rules (e.g., motor vehicle, pedestrian, cycling) in the home, community, and school.
Explain the need for rules to promote safety, and explain how decisions to follow or disregard safety guidelines have consequences for self and others.
Explain how a clean school, home, and community environments prevent the spread of germs.
Describe how people who are caring and encouraging help their friends feel good about themselves and positively impact the health of their school and community.
Explain how teasing or making fun of people with differences hurts feelings and negatively affects the social and emotional health of the school and community.
Communicate how clean school and community environments prevent the spread of germs.
Describe how access to recreational opportunities impacts community health.
Describe ways to prevent injuries at school and in the community.
Analyze how local sources of pollution can influence both personal and community health.
Analyze how unhealthy social environments influence personal health.
Define healthcare disparities that exist in the community and analyze how poverty, race, class, and gender have contributed to those disparities.
Human Body Systems
Identify basic parts of the body, such as the head, arms, and legs.
Describe the basic functions of the five senses.
Name and locate the basic body parts and their functions.
Name and locate the basic body organs, including the heart, brain, lungs, skin, and stomach, and describe their functions.
Describe the benefits of getting adequate sleep (e.g., to aid in the growth and repair of the body).
Describe how the skeletal and muscular systems help humans move and protect parts of the body.
Explain that bodies change as they grow older.
List factors that contribute to healthy physical growth and make each one of us unique.

Describe the basic structure and functions of the following human body systems:
  • the respiratory system
  • the digestive system
Identify life stages and the physical changes that occur at each stage.

Describe the basic structure and functions of the following human body systems:
  • the circulatory system
  • the nervous system
  • the cardiovascular system
Identify major muscles and bones.

Describe the basic structure and functions of the following human body systems:
  • the excretory system
  • the reproductive system
  • endocrine system
Describe how muscles and bones are interrelated.
Human Growth & Development
Describe the interconnection of all the body systems and how they work together to ensure wellness.
Describe the components, functions, and processes of the reproductive system, and key developmental and body changes during puberty, including menstruation.
Explain how heredity, physiological changes, environmental influences, and varying social experiences contribute to one's growth and development.
Sexuality, Reproduction & Health
Describe the physical differences and similarities of gender.
Describe how individual bodies are different sizes, shapes, and colors, but are equally special, including those that are disabled.
Explain that talking to parents and other trusted adults about sexuality can be helpful.
Describe the physical, social, and emotional changes that occur at puberty.
Explain how the health of the mother affects the development of the fetus.
Explain that people, regardless of biological sex, gender, ability, sexual orientation, gender identity, and culture, have sexual feelings and the need for love, affection, and physical intimacy.
Identify sexual feelings common to young adolescents; differentiate between having sexual feelings and acting on them.

Describe the signs and symptoms of pregnancy and the potential challenges faced by adolescent parents and their families; and explain that sometimes women become pregnant when they do not want or are unable to care for a child.

Describe the causes and symptoms of, and myths about, HIV; describe what it means when someone in the family has HIV, including the fact that persons living with AIDS can live a long and healthy life.
Explain the benefits of abstinence; postponing sexual behavior; and setting limits on sexual behavior.
Explain the negative repercussions of dating violence.
Describe short-term and long-term consequences of adolescent sexual activity, and the benefits of abstinence as the most effective means of contraception.
Differentiate healthy sexual behaviors (abstinence) from those that are harmful (date rape, sexual promiscuity); and identify barriers and supports.
Analyze the social, cultural, religious, and legal factors that influence the choice and use of contraception; and the choice to remain abstinent.
Compare and contrast the major symptoms of most STIs, indicating that many have no symptoms, and explain the serious consequences of going untreated.
Describe the symptoms of, prognosis for, and ways to assist family members and friends who suffer from HIV/AIDS, including how to decrease acts of discrimination and stigma.

Define sexual orientation, using correct terminology; and explain that as people grow and develop they may begin to feel romantically and/or sexually attracted to people of a different gender and/or to people of the same gender.
Explain the importance of testing both partners for HIV and STIs before sexual behavior and the risks and precautions of birth delivery when HIV and STIs are present.
Compare and contrast the theories about what determines sexual orientation, including genetics; prenatal, social, and cultural influences; psychosocial factors; and a combination of all of these.
Describe why abstinence and contraception are important.
Describe fertilization, embryonic development, and fetal development; and discuss prenatal practices that support a healthy pregnancy.
Describe the physical and emotional changes that occur during each stage of pregnancy and the importance of regular prenatal care.
Sexuality, Reproduction & Health, Sexual Transmitted Infections (STI)
Define STIs and HIV/AIDS; describe behaviors that place one at risk for HIV/AIDS, STIs, or unintended pregnancy; and explain why abstinence is the most effective way to prevent disease or pregnancy.
Discuss strategies to remain abstinent and resist pressures to become sexually active.
Disease Prevention & Treatment
Identify common signs of illnesses in children, such as a runny nose, coughing, and sneezing, and methods of prevention.
Explain that medicines prescribed by a doctor are used to help people who are hurt or sick.
Summarize how many childhood illnesses can be prevented or treated (e.g., by hand washing, immunizations, not sharing cups or combs, covering coughs and sneezes).
Explain how regular health check-ups and screening can prevent, detect, and treat health problems and why diseases and health conditions need to be detected and treated early.

Distinguish among communicable, non-communicable, acute, chronic, and inherited diseases and health conditions; and explain that some diseases and health conditions are preventable and others are not.
Demonstrate how to follow universal precautions for preventing infection when someone is bleeding or one encounters used needles.
Explain that bacteria and viruses cause infectious diseases that lead to common illnesses, including sexually transmitted diseases.
Describe how sanitation and waste disposal, and environmental controls help to prevent diseases and health conditions.
Develop strategies for proper food-handling and storage to prevent food-borne illness.
Explain the importance of practicing health-promoting behaviors, such as wellness check-ups, breast and testicular self-exams, and early identification of potential problems.
Compare and contrast prevention and treatment of diseases and health conditions prevalent in adolescents, including obesity, diabetes, Lyme disease, STIs, and HIV/AIDS.
Assess the use of public health strategies to prevent diseases and improve health conditions.
Illustrate how pathogens, family history, and other risk factors are related to the cause or prevention of disease and other health problems, such as high blood pressure.
Describe how exposure to allergens and other environmental triggers can cause allergic reactions and asthma attacks.

Recognize that proper diet, exercise, rest, and avoidance of risk behaviors, such as smoking, drinking, and other substance use, contribute to the health of a pregnant woman and positively impact the development of the fetus.
Nutrition
Explain why healthy bodies require rest, exercise, and good nutrition.
Sort foods according to food groups and food sources.
Identify factors that lead to becoming overweight or obese.
Differentiate between healthy and unhealthy food choices and how they might lead to becoming overweight or obese.
Explain why one should limit foods that are high in fats, sugars, and sodium which can lead to a variety of health problems.

Differentiate between healthy and unhealthy eating habits by using the USDA Food Guide Pyramid and its three major concepts of balance, variety, and moderation which help to improve fitness and performance (e.g., identify foods that serve as healthy snacks).
Classify foods by nutritional content and nutritional value, and use food product labels to make informed decisions regarding food, and explain how diet and rest improve fitness and performance.
Explain how nutrition affects personal health, academic achievement, fitness and performance, including the effects of malnutrition on brain functioning.
Compare food choices based on nutrient content and value, calories, and cost to create a healthy meal plan.
Describe the affect of nutrients on the functioning of human body systems, with particular attention to diet needs during the adolescent growth spurt.
Explain that a body mass index is a general indicator of overall fitness.
Describe the benefits of a high-fiber diet (e.g., plenty of grains and fruit) to help food and waste products move through the body systems and prevent diseases.
Discuss the short-term and long-term benefits and risks associated with nutritional choices, such as heart disease, high cholesterol, cancer, and osteoporosis.
Differentiate between being overweight and being obese; and research and recommend healthy ways to lose, gain or maintain weight.
Alcohol, Tobacco & Other Drugs
Discuss how first- and second-hand cigarette smoke impact the environment and the health of oneself and others.
Compare and contrast the differences between helpful medicines and harmful drugs.
Distinguish between legal and illegal drugs and give examples of each.
Explain how to use medicine properly (e.g., under particular circumstances and with the supervision of a trusted adult).
Explain that it is illegal to use or possess certain drugs and substances.
Describe the purpose of medicines (prescription and over-the-counter) and how they can be used or misused in the treatment of common medical problems.
Describe the short-term and long-term harmful effects of tobacco use and second-hand/passive smoke on the body and its organ systems.
Describe the short-term and long-term harmful effects of alcohol abuse on the body and its organ systems.
Define addiction to alcohol, tobacco, and other drugs; and explain that those who are addicted require assistance to stop addiction.
Describe various methods for addiction prevention, intervention, treatment, and recovery.
Identify internal and external factors that influence the decision of young people to use or not to use alcohol or drugs.
Demonstrate ways of refusing tobacco, alcohol, and other drugs from peers and ways of sharing preventive health information.
Explain the physical, legal, financial, social, and psychological cost of the use, sale, and possession of illegal substances.
Describe the signs and symptoms of substance abuse, factors that contribute to the abuse, stages that lead to dependency, and ways that family and friends can support a drug-free lifestyle.
Explain the relationship between injected drug use and diseases such as HIV/AIDS and hepatitis.
Explain the consequences of driving under the influence of alcohol and other drugs; and develop strategies to prevent drinking and driving in order to maintain personal, family, and community health.
Discuss how the use of alcohol and other drugs impairs decision-making; increases the risk of violence; and places one at risk for sexual assault, pregnancy, and STIs.
Students demonstrate the ability to access and evaluate health information, products, and services.
Locate Health Information & Assistance
Understand and follow emergency procedures.
Demonstrate appropriate trust in adults; and discuss roles and responsibilities of family or community members who promote the welfare and safety of children and adults.
Demonstrate the ability to call 911 in an emergency; and know personal information, such as the address and phone number.
Identify basic signs, symbols and warning labels (e.g., a poison symbol on a container).
Identify parents, teachers, and doctors as people who provide valid health information.
Explain the meaning of common signs, symbols, and warning labels.

Demonstrate the ability to seek help when feeling ill (from police, fire and emergency care personnel) and to locate resources from home, school, and the community that can provide valid health information.
Obtain basic information from the product safety labels of household products; and understand the effects of misusing them.
Demonstrate the ability to locate medical, dental, and other health-related resources in the community, such as public health agencies.
Analyze information from the labels of health-related products.

Demonstrate the ability to locate and describe the services provided by voluntary health organizations, such as the World Health Organization, the American Red Cross, and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
Analyze the labels of over-the-counter medicines to determine their active ingredients and uses, warnings related to their use, and directions for correct use.

Identify characteristics of valid health products as ones that are approved by trusted sources, such as the Food and Drug Administration, the Consumer Product Safety Commission, and Internet sites that often end in .gov or .org.
Compare generic and brand name products for cost and validity.
Identify agencies that specialize in working with young people and provide services for teenagers.
Demonstrate the ability to access valid mental health information from schools (e.g., the school psychologist) and community sources (e.g., a local mental health association).
Develop guidelines for the use of professional health services based on the type of care needed, the nature of the problem, and the kind of questions that need answering.
Students demonstrate the ability to apply self-management skills to enhance personal health and safety.
Personal Health & Hygiene

Perform basic hygiene and self-help tasks, including washing hands before meals and after toileting, brushing teeth after meals, wiping the nose with a tissue, and covering the mouth when coughing or sneezing with the elbow or a tissue.

Demonstrate personal hygiene skills:
  • correctly wash one's hands
  • wear appropriate attire for weather and sports
  • use the proper technique for brushing and flossing one's teeth
Describe and demonstrate self-care practices that promote cleanliness and hygiene, such as correct handwashing, regular bathing, and washing clothes.
Assess one's personal hygiene habits and determine whether there are areas needing improvement.
Describe and demonstrate self-care practices for skin, hair, and nails.
Explain how cleanliness and good grooming show consideration for oneself and others.
Describe ways to promote cleanliness and good grooming, including the selection of personal hygiene products (e.g., use of sanitary products or deodorants).

Describe and demonstrate strategies to improve or maintain personal health, including strategies for protecting eyes (e.g., sunglasses), ears (e.g., volume reduction), and skin (e.g., sun protection).
Safety Skills
Understand and follow health and safety rules at home and school.
Understand and follow classroom routines and rules and know how to handle transitions.
Explain how childhood injuries can be prevented or treated through the use of seat belts, child safety seats in motor vehicles, and protective gear while cycling.
Demonstrate ways to avoid trouble and how to seek help in threatening situations (e.g., yell "no" and seek help from a trusted adult when a stranger approaches).
Identify substances that should never be consumed or inhaled, such as drug look-alikes, glue, cleaning fluids and other poisons, and the reasons why.
Describe and demonstrate basic traffic and pedestrian safety skills needed to avoid injury (e.g., crossing streets, bicycle safety).
Understand that one's body is one's own and that no one has the right to touch another in a way that makes the other feel uncomfortable.
Distinguish between a good/safe touch, a bad/unsafe touch and a confusing touch; and explain what to do if touching causes uncomfortable feelings.
Describe and demonstrate basic fire and water safety skills.

Describe and demonstrate appropriate and safe behavior when interacting with strangers, acquaintances and trusted adults, including how to say "no" firmly, state a reason, and get help from a trusted adult.

Demonstrate how to avoid and reduce compromising and/or threatening situations (e.g., uncomfortable sexual attention), and explain why it is very important to tell a trusted adult if one has been sexually abused or hurt in any way.
Demonstrate how to be safe around strangers, ask trusted adults for help when lost or in trouble, and always tell family members where and with whom one is going.
Explain how the use of safety gear helps prevent injuries when exercising.
Describe ways to avoid and reduce threatening situations from extreme weather systems.
Recognize and deal with common hazards when walking or cycling on the sidewalk.
Describe and demonstrate simple first-aid procedures.
Explain how to stay safe around weapons, including telling a trusted adult about the existence of a weapon at school.
Compare and contrast the incidence and characteristics of intentional and unintentional injuries in adolescents, and describe the health risks associated with feelings of immortality.
Analyze the short-term and long-term impacts of injuries on individuals and families, and develop strategies to reduce the incidence of such injuries.
Describe and demonstrate basic first-aid procedures.
Demonstrate safety strategies for the care of babies and young children.
Define common risk factors associated with teen dating violence ( e.g., alcohol, drugs, lack of parental supervision)
Students demonstrate the ability to analyze the influence of family, culture, media, and technology on health and health behaviors.
Family & Cultural Influences
Identify and value characteristics of oneself, one's family, and one's community.
Recognize the abilities and accomplishments of self and others, and talk about how people can be helpful or hurtful to one another.
Explain that there are different kinds of families, and children may live with one or more caregivers.
Describe how families show love for each other and how changes in a family (e.g., births, divorce, employment changes, illnesses, deaths) may make its members feel happy or sad.
Describe how families take care of one another and set rules to help members live together healthily.
Explain that individuals have different cultural backgrounds that influence dietary customs and recreational activities.
Describe how children and adult family members can serve as role models for healthy behaviors (e.g., eating healthily, exercising) and influence choices for health care.
Describe how family members can influence personal decisions to abstain from unhealthy practices, such as alcohol and other drug use, and advocate for healthful practices.
Describe how families and cultures have different norms for, and attach different meanings to, verbal and nonverbal communication (e.g., in their sense of personal space, use of touch, eye contact).
Identify ways children can model healthful behaviors for family members.
Describe ways in which relationships among parents and children change during adolescence, including the relative impact of peer and parental influences.

Explain that children learn most of their values from parents and other family members regarding important decisions about friends, sexual relationships, family, education, and a range of other issues.
Explain the family life cycle and what it means to be a parent in various cultures.

Recognize that raising a child is one of the most important functions of a family; and describe the consequences of teen parenting from the perspectives of the teen mother, teen father, and parents of the teens.
Specify ways adolescents can advocate for personal, family and community health.
Media & Technological Influences
Explain how media advertisements encourage children to want certain types of products (e.g., free prizes) by using cartoon characters, catchy phrases, famous people, or other strategies.
Describe the positive and negative influence of the media on thoughts, feelings, perceptions, and health behaviors.
Explain how radio, television, and new forms of technology (e.g., the Internet) give us health and safety information.
Explain how the media make certain physical traits seem desirable (e.g., extreme thinness, bulky muscles) without regard to the risky behaviors that can cause those traits.
Analyze how the media send mixed messages about alcohol, tobacco use, and violence.

Analyze how societal messages from all media, including music, television programs, movies, advertising, and the Internet influence adolescents' perceptions and behaviors related to sexual activity, diet and body image.

Analyze how societal messages from all media, including music, television programs, movies, advertising, and the Internet influence adolescents' perceptions and behaviors related to sexual activity, diet and body image, alcohol, drug use and violence.

Describe the ways technology can affect personal health and health behaviors for better and for worse, such as through new, effective medicines; improved exercise equipment; and the availability and nutrient quality of food.
Students demonstrate the ability to utilize interpersonal communication skills to enhance and protect health.
Effective & Respectful Communication
Participate in group activities and demonstrate responsive and reciprocal skills during the interaction.
Play cooperatively with other children.
Recognize the feelings and rights of others and respond appropriately.
Observe and use appropriate ways of interacting in a group: take turns to talk, listen to peers, ask questions, wait for an answer, and gain the floor in appropriate ways.
Stand up for the rights of self and others.
Describe verbal and nonverbal communication to express feelings, including the impact of gestures and facial expressions.
Respect the property, rights, and personal space of others.
Demonstrate how to ask for help and say what one wants in a positive and polite manner.
Demonstrate the ability to match nonverbal communication with verbal communication to express feelings.
Describe the characteristics needed to be a responsible family member and friend, such as being a person who helps, shares, listens, and is kind and polite.
Explain how friends can feel angry and sometimes hurt one another, yet remain friends.
Demonstrate how to show respect for others by the way one behaves, talks, and touches, including how not to interrupt or talk when someone else is talking.
Explain how failing to listen, yelling, blaming, criticizing, and/or name-calling impair communication.
Demonstrate how to express concern for a friend or family member who has been hurt or has a problem.
Demonstrate how to show respect for others by the way one behaves, talks, and touches, including how not to interrupt or talk when someone else is talking.
Demonstrate effective verbal and nonverbal communication skills to enhance health, including how to use body language and tone of voice to say "no."
Explain reasons and demonstrate how to use "I" messages instead of "you" messages to express feelings.

Demonstrate how to communicate respect for others by being sensitive to the needs and feelings of someone who is different (e.g., a student with a disability) or someone whom they do not know (e.g., a new student).
Explain that when people hold the belief that all members of a group will behave the same way, it is called a stereotype, and stereotypes can hurt people.
Apply attentive listening, feedback, and assertiveness skills (rather than passive or aggressive forms of communication) to enhance positive interpersonal communication.
Demonstrate how to initiate and sustain conversation with another person by identifying oneself and discussing experiences, interests, and shared values.
Describe the concepts of prejudice and discrimination and how they can lead to unequal opportunities and negative consequences for the individual and society as a whole.
Describe how to demonstrate care and concern toward ill and disabled persons in one's family, school, and community.
Demonstrate how to provide constructive criticism, including selecting the right time/place; focusing on things that can be changed; and providing advice that is positive, specific, and helpful.
Resolving Conflicts
Discuss ways to solve or prevent problems, and display problem-solving skills , such as seeking adult assistance to resolve a conflict or taking turns with a toy.
Use negotiation skills to resolve conflicts.
Understand that actions have consequences.
Identify the possible causes of conflict and discuss appropriate ways to prevent and resolve conflicts, such as how to share and take turns when playing with classmates.
Differentiate between negative and positive behaviors used in conflict situations (e.g., name calling and hitting vs. trying to see the other person's point of view and compromising).
Summarize ways to use nonviolent strategies to resolve conflict and compromise in a manner that is fair to all persons involved.
Describe strategies to handle and avoid fights with bullies.
Explain that negotiation requires give and take on the part of all of the people involved, and that negotiation is a way to compromise with others without using guilt, anger, or intimidation.
Demonstrate how to resolve a conflict by showing how to stay calm, assess the risk of violence, and leave if a weapon is present.
Analyze possible causes and results of conflicts among youth in communities, such as hurt feelings, jealousy, power/leadership struggles, and prejudice.
Explain alternatives to gang-related behaviors and acts of violence.
Advocate for and defend healthy conflict-resolution strategies.
Analyze the possible causes of conflict in families, such as hurt feelings, jealousy, desire for independence, and privacy; and discuss possible solutions.
Compare the use of cooperative and competitive strategies to achieve a group goal, and recommend strategies to keep a group on target and free from conflict.
Students demonstrate the ability to implement decision-making and goal-setting skills to enhance health.
Decision-Making & Goal-Setting
Take responsibility for own health and well-being by demonstrating steps to solve a personal health problem (e.g., hand washing, telling an adult when they are ill or hurt).
Demonstrate the ability to complete tasks.
Predict outcomes of positive health decisions.
Predict how decisions regarding various health behaviors have consequences for oneself.
Apply responsible decision-making skills, including identifying and making choices and explaining the consequences of each choice.
Explain the steps to making an effective health decision, set a short-term personal health goal (e.g., improving diet or sleep habits), and track progress toward its achievement.

Set achievable and purposeful personal health goals (e.g., goals for physical activity based on the results of physical fitness testing), outline a series of steps to meet those goals, and track progress toward their achievement.
Use health data to set achievable and purposeful short-term and long-term health goals that address strengths, needs, and health risks; and track progress toward their achievement.

Demonstrate the ability to work with others in a decision-making process that includes identifying choices and examining the alternatives and consequences of each choice when making decisions related to health issues and problems.
Design a purposeful personal health goal (e.g., healthy eating), evaluate how family and peers might support or hinder its achievement, and evaluate progress toward its achievement.

Demonstrate the ability to identify choices on a range of health issues that are consistent with one's own values, and do not involve risking one's own health or safety, other people's health or safety, or breaking the law.

Evaluate home-safety conditions (e.g., proper use of smoke detectors and fire extinguishers) and workplace conditions (e.g., eye protection, gloves, and hard hats) for perceived and actual risk of intentional and unintentional injuries; and apply injury prevention and management strategies.

Identify the signs of emotional and physical abuse and the available resources for help and support in the schools, the local community, law enforcement agencies, and faith-based groups.
Level 2
Safety Skills
Demonstrate ways to avoid, reduce, and report dating violence and sexual assaults.
Identify the health consequences of domestic violence, child abuse, rape, and other forms of violence; and discuss strategies to deal with and prevent them.
Students demonstrate the ability to analyze the influence of family, culture, media, and technology on health and health behaviors.
Level 1
Family & Cultural Influences

Identify the traits of a healthy family, including responsibility, communication, trust, loyalty, respect, commitment, love, affirmation, and self-reliance; and explain the ways family members depend on one another and can positively influence each other's health decisions.
Media & Technological Influences
Describe the role of government agencies in regulating advertising claims related to health that appears in the media and on the Internet.
Level 2
Family & Cultural Influences
Identify the financial resources and child-rearing skills (including the emotional maturity required to nurture children and a knowledge of child-development stages) needed for parenting.
Media & Technological Influences
Research and evaluate the impact of medical technology on personal, family, and community health.
Students demonstrate the ability to utilize interpersonal communication skills to enhance and protect health.
Level 1
Effective & Respectful Communication
Contrast how positive communication (e.g., active listening, praise, and humor) and negative communication (e.g., teasing, name calling, and bullying) impact relationships.
Explain the importance of mutual respect and communication as key elements to successful dating and setting limits in sexual relationships.
Level 2
Effective & Respectful Communication
Explain the importance of responsibility and character traits such as love, respectfulness, generosity, kindness, and forgiveness in committed relationships.
Students demonstrate the ability to implement decision-making and goal-setting skills to enhance health.
Level 1
Decision-Making & Goal-Setting
Work cooperatively with others to identify potential solutions to personal, family, or community health concerns; and use risk-benefit ratios to make decisions.
Explain the importance of establishing a long-term relationship with a primary care provider as a critical component in maintaining one's health.
Level 2
Decision-Making & Goal-Setting
Formulate plans of action to address the health needs of individuals at various life stages (e.g., plans to secure well-baby and childcare for infants and young children).
Demonstrate kind and respectful ways to end relationships, postpone sexual involvement, and remain abstinent.
